Course: CSE0001 – Digital Literacy | VIT Bhopal University
Focus: Online Safety for College Students in India

General Online Safety

1 Never share your OTP, UPI PIN, CVV, or internet banking password with anyone — not with someone claiming to be from your bank, customer care, or even a government helpline. No legitimate service will ever ask for these over a call or message.
2 Do not click on links sent via WhatsApp, SMS, or email that ask you to log in to your bank, payment app, or any account. Always open apps directly from your phone's home screen or the official website.
3 Verify unknown callers claiming to represent a bank or company: hang up, independently look up the organisation's official phone number (from their website, not from Google ads), and call them back yourself.
4 Enable two-factor authentication (2FA) on all financial apps, email accounts, and social media platforms. This ensures that even if your password is stolen, your account remains protected.
5 Download apps only from the official Google Play Store or Apple App Store. Never install apps from links sent via SMS, WhatsApp, or email — these are frequently malware-infected.
6 Use strong, unique passwords for each account. A strong password is at least 12 characters long and mixes uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols (e.g., V!t#Bh0p4l$25). Use a password manager if needed.


UPI and Financial Safety ⚠️

1 You never need to enter your UPI PIN to receive money. If anyone tells you to enter your PIN to "accept" a payment or refund — it is a scam. End the call immediately.
2 Always verify the UPI ID or scan the QR code carefully before confirming any payment. A single character difference in a UPI ID (e.g., shop@okaxis vs sh0p@okaxis) redirects your money to a fraudster. Double-check the name that appears after entering the UPI ID before hitting Pay.


Social Media and Account Safety

1 Do not post publicly about recent purchases, grievances with e-commerce platforms, or financial transactions. Fraudsters actively monitor such posts to identify and target victims.
2 Log out of accounts on shared devices — college computer labs, library systems, or friends' phones.


If You Are a Victim — Report Immediately

Speed is critical. The faster you report, the higher the chance of freezing the fraudster's account before funds are withdrawn.

StepAction1Call 1930 (National Cyber Crime Helpline — 24x7, toll-free) immediately.2File an online complaint at cybercrime.gov.in with full transaction details.3Call your bank's customer care to report the fraud and request a transaction freeze.4Visit your nearest police station to file an FIR if the amount is significant.5Save all evidence: screenshots of messages, call logs, UPI transaction IDs.
